# excalidraw-app security

## Environment and secrets

- Read sensitive values only from `import.meta.env` / build-time env as documented in `docs/technical/dev-setup.md`. Never hardcode production keys in source.
- Ensure `.env` files with secrets stay out of git (verify `.gitignore` when adding new env file names).

## Collaboration and realtime

- Treat room IDs, session payloads, and socket messages as untrusted until validated. Do not execute code or inject HTML based on peer messages without sanitization.
- Do not send authentication material to untrusted origins; align with existing collab and Firebase configuration.

## Service worker and PWA

- Changes to `registerSW` / service worker caching: avoid caching sensitive authenticated responses unless that behavior is explicitly intended and safe.

## Analytics and errors (e.g. Sentry)

- Scrub or avoid attaching secrets, tokens, or full document payloads to error reports when not necessary.

## Vite / HTML entry

- Avoid injecting arbitrary scripts or inline handlers from user-controlled or remote config. Keep script sources explicit and trusted.

## Third-party scripts

- Adding analytics, chat widgets, or external scripts requires explicit review (CSP, data leakage, subresource integrity where applicable).

## Disclose in chat

When this rule materially guides your response or edits, state in the Cursor chat that you applied it — mention `.cursor/rules/security-excalidraw-app.mdc` (one short line is enough).

## How to verify

- Confirm secrets and env-specific values come from `import.meta.env` / documented env as in `docs/technical/dev-setup.md`, not hardcoded in `excalidraw-app`.
- Review collab/socket and Firebase-related code for validation of untrusted payloads; after changes, run app build and smoke-test collab if applicable.
